INSERT INTO Users_question VALUES(3,'{''1. Valine''}','{''2. Leucine''}','{''3. Glutamic acid''}','{''4. Phenylalanine''}','{''Incorrect. Valine is an aliphatic, nonpolar amino acid. Nonpolar amino acids tend to cluster in the interior of proteins to avoid contact with water. A common mistake is to forget that valine is nonpolar and associate it with some sort of polarity because it has no charge; therefore, a person may think that it will be found on the surface interacting with the water.''}','{''Incorrect. Leucine is another aliphatic, nonpolar amino acid. Like valine, it prefers to reside in the hydrophobic core of the protein. Students can be confused as to where certain amino acids are found within proteins, but it must be remembered that nonpolar amino acids tend to be buried within the protein structure away from the aqueous environment. ''}','{''Correct. Glutamic acid is a negatively charged, polar amino acid at physiological pH. Charged and polar amino acids are hydrophilic, readily interacting with water and thus are commonly found on the protein surface. A common pitfall is not remembering the charge or polarity of the amino acids and thinking that it may be buried within the protein structure.''}','{"Incorrect. Phenylalanine contains a large, hydrophobic aromatic ring. Due to its nonpolar nature, it''s usually found in the interior of the protein, avoiding the aqueous environment. Although some aromatic residues can be found on the surface, phenylalanine''s overall hydrophobicity makes it less likely than a charged amino acid like glutamic acid. Students may consider aromatic rings to have some polar character because of the pi electrons; however, in phenylalanine, the ring is predominantly nonpolar."}',3,2,'Which of the following amino acids is MOST likely to be found on the surface of a protein in an aqueous solution?');
INSERT INTO Users_question VALUES(4,'{''1.  Compare the self-reported happiness levels of residents who were displaced with those who remained in the neighborhood.''}','{''2.  Analyze publicly available health records (e.g., hospital visits, prescriptions) of displaced residents before and after the gentrification occurred, and compare the changes to a control group of similar individuals who did not experience displacement.''}','{''3.  Conduct interviews with community leaders to gather their perspectives on the impact of gentrification on the well-being of residents.''}','{''4.  Track the employment rates of displaced residents one year after the gentrification occurred and compare them to the national average employment rate.''}','{"This option is weak because self-reported happiness is a subjective measure and may be influenced by factors other than displacement, such as personality traits or current life events.  It doesn''t account for pre-displacement happiness levels. It also doesn''t control for potential confounding variables. A common pitfall is assuming that a subjective measure is sufficient to demonstrate a causal relationship. Furthermore, even if the displaced residents report lower happiness, it doesn''t necessarily mean it''s *caused* by the displacement; it could be correlated for other reasons.  A stronger design would involve more objective and longitudinal measures."}','{''This is the STRONGEST option. Analyzing health records provides a more objective measure of well-being than self-reported happiness.  Comparing pre- and post-displacement health records for the displaced group allows researchers to assess changes within the same individuals. Crucially, including a control group of similar individuals who did not experience displacement helps to isolate the effect of displacement from other factors that might influence health outcomes over time. This design controls for confounding variables and provides a basis for causal inference.  This design minimizes bias and provides a robust comparison.''}','{''This option relies on qualitative data from community leaders, which can be valuable for understanding the broader context but is not sufficient to establish a causal relationship between displacement and well-being. Community leader perspectives might be biased or incomplete.  It lacks objective measures and a control group, making it difficult to determine whether any observed changes are directly attributable to displacement.  A pitfall is relying solely on subjective perspectives without empirical data. This research is helpful in creating a hypothesis but not testing one.''}','{''This option only focuses on one aspect of well-being (employment) and does not provide a comprehensive assessment of overall well-being. Comparing to the national average is problematic because the displaced residents might have had different pre-existing employment rates or face different local labor market conditions than the national average.  It also lacks a control group and does not consider pre-displacement employment rates of the displaced group. A common pitfall is using an inappropriate comparison group (national average) rather than a more relevant control group (similar individuals who were not displaced) and a single factor does not tell the whole story.''}',2,32,'Researchers are studying the effects of gentrification on a low-income neighborhood. They find that after a new luxury apartment complex is built, rents in the surrounding area increase significantly, leading to displacement of many long-term residents. The researchers hypothesize that this displacement leads to a decrease in overall well-being for the displaced residents. To test this hypothesis, which of the following research designs would provide the STRONGEST evidence?');
INSERT INTO Users_question VALUES(5,'{''1) Valine to Alanine''}','{''2) Lysine to Arginine''}','{''3) Serine to Phenylalanine''}','{''4) Glutamate to Aspartate''}','{"Incorrect. Both valine and alanine are nonpolar, hydrophobic amino acids. While alanine is smaller than valine, the overall hydrophobic nature of the side chain is maintained. This conservative substitution is less likely to drastically disrupt protein folding or cause aggregation, as the hydrophobic interactions driving protein folding would still be largely intact.  A common pitfall is assuming any change will drastically alter the protein''s behavior; sometimes, the changes are subtle, and the protein can still function normally, or near-normally."}','{"Incorrect. Both lysine and arginine are positively charged, basic amino acids.  While arginine is slightly bulkier than lysine, they both can form similar ionic and hydrogen bond interactions within the protein. This is another conservative substitution. Replacing one positively charged amino acid with another is unlikely to have a major effect on protein folding. Students might incorrectly assume that ''changing the charge'' is always a big deal, but here, the charge is maintained, so the protein''s electrostatic interactions are not significantly disrupted."}','{"Correct. Serine is a polar, hydrophilic amino acid, while phenylalanine is a large, nonpolar, hydrophobic amino acid. Replacing a polar, hydrophilic amino acid with a large, nonpolar, hydrophobic one introduces a significant change in the amino acid''s properties. This substitution is most likely to disrupt the protein''s folding and lead to aggregation, because now the protein will likely be unable to form hydrogen bonds with the aqueous environment, causing the protein to collapse onto itself. The bulky hydrophobic side chain of phenylalanine will disrupt the existing hydrogen bonding network and promote hydrophobic interactions that could lead to misfolding and aggregation. This is a non-conservative substitution. Pay close attention to the hydrophobicity/hydrophilicity changes."}','{"Incorrect. Both glutamate and aspartate are negatively charged, acidic amino acids. Aspartate is simply a shorter version of glutamate. This is a conservative substitution; while there may be some subtle shifts in the protein''s structure, the negative charge is retained, and the side chains are still relatively small.  The protein''s ability to form ionic bonds and hydrogen bonds at that location would likely be maintained. Students may overthink the importance of the slight size difference between these two amino acids, missing the key similarity in their charge and polarity."}',3,2,'A researcher is studying a novel protein that appears to be misfolding and aggregating in the cell, leading to cellular dysfunction. They hypothesize that a specific amino acid substitution in the protein''s primary sequence is responsible for this misfolding. To investigate this, they create several mutant versions of the protein, each with a single amino acid change at the suspected site. They then express these mutant proteins in cells and assess their folding and aggregation properties. Which of the following amino acid substitutions would be MOST likely to disrupt the protein''s folding and lead to aggregation?');
INSERT INTO Users_question VALUES(6,'{''1. Glutamic acid''}','{''2. Lysine''}','{''3. Valine''}','{''4. Histidine''}','{''Incorrect. Glutamic acid is a negatively charged (acidic) amino acid. Charged amino acids are hydrophilic and prefer to interact with aqueous environments. They are unlikely to be found in the hydrophobic core of a transmembrane domain. A common pitfall is not recognizing the properties of glutamic acid (charged, hydrophilic) and how those properties dictate its location within a protein.''}','{"Incorrect. Lysine is a positively charged (basic) amino acid. Like glutamic acid, it''s hydrophilic and prefers aqueous environments. It would be energetically unfavorable for lysine to reside within the hydrophobic transmembrane region. A common pitfall is forgetting the basic amino acids and their hydrophilic nature."}','{''Correct. Valine is a nonpolar, hydrophobic amino acid. Transmembrane domains span the lipid bilayer of a cell membrane, which is a highly hydrophobic environment. Hydrophobic amino acids like valine are favored in this region because they minimize unfavorable interactions with the hydrophobic lipid tails. This interaction stabilizes the protein within the membrane. A common pitfall is overlooking the importance of hydrophobicity in transmembrane domains.''}','{"Incorrect. Histidine can be charged or uncharged depending on the pH. While it can sometimes be found near the membrane surface where it can participate in interactions with the polar head groups of lipids, it is less likely to be buried deeply within the transmembrane domain compared to a strictly hydrophobic amino acid like valine. Histidine''s imidazole side chain has a pKa close to physiological pH, making it more likely to be involved in catalysis or proton transfer at the protein surface. A common pitfall is thinking that because histidine *can* be uncharged under certain conditions, it''s a good candidate for a transmembrane domain, without considering how pH affects its protonation state, and the presence of more favorable hydrophobic options."}',3,2,'Which of the following amino acids is most likely to be found in the transmembrane domain of a protein?');
INSERT INTO Users_question VALUES(7,'{''1. E. coli cells that have not been transformed with any plasmid.''}','{''2. E. coli cells transformed with a plasmid containing the Foldase gene with a premature stop codon early in the sequence.''}','{''3. E. coli cells transformed with a plasmid containing the wild-type (non-mutated) Foldase gene.''}','{''4. Purified, commercially available bovine serum albumin (BSA).''}','{"Incorrect. While using untransformed E. coli cells can provide a baseline for cellular components, it doesn''t account for the effects of expressing the Foldase protein itself (unmutated). The CD signal from untransformed cells will be very different from that of cells expressing Foldase, making it difficult to isolate the impact of the mutations. Many cellular proteins have secondary structure and would obscure the signal from Foldase. This option fails to isolate the variable of interest (the mutations) and does not control for Foldase expression."}','{''Incorrect. This control would result in truncated protein, which would most likely be degraded by the cell. Even if not degraded the protein would be too short to form any secondary structure or have a dramatically different secondary structure content than the full length Foldase protein. The goal is to maintain the protein under the same conditions without the mutation.''}','{"Correct. The most appropriate control group is E. coli cells transformed with a plasmid containing the wild-type Foldase gene. This control ensures that the baseline folding and CD spectrum of the normal, functional protein are established. By comparing the CD spectra of the mutated Foldase proteins to that of the wild-type Foldase, the researcher can accurately determine how each mutation affects the protein''s secondary structure and, by inference, its overall folding. This control accounts for the effects of expressing the Foldase protein, the presence of the plasmid, and any other factors related to the expression and purification process, leaving the mutation as the sole variable. This is the standard to which the mutated proteins are compared."}','{''Incorrect. BSA is a different protein altogether and will have a distinct amino acid sequence and secondary structure composition compared to Foldase. While BSA is often used as a protein standard, it does not control for any of the factors specific to Foldase expression, purification, or inherent folding properties. Comparing the CD spectrum of mutated Foldase to that of BSA would not provide meaningful information about the impact of the mutations on Foldase folding. The differences observed would be due to the inherent differences between the two proteins, not the mutations.''}',3,2,replace('A researcher is studying the effect of mutations on the folding of a protein called ''Foldase''. Foldase normally folds into a specific tertiary structure crucial for its function. The researcher introduces several point mutations in the Foldase gene, expresses the mutated proteins in E. coli, and then purifies them. To assess the impact of each mutation on protein folding, the researcher uses circular dichroism (CD) spectroscopy. CD spectroscopy measures the difference in absorbance of left- and right-circularly polarized light, which is sensitive to the secondary structure content of proteins. \n\nWhich of the following would be the MOST appropriate control group for this experiment?','\n',char(10)));
INSERT INTO Users_question VALUES(8,'{''1. Alanine to Valine''}','{''2. Lysine to Arginine''}','{''3. Glycine to Proline''}','{''4. Serine to Threonine''}','{''Alanine and Valine are both nonpolar, aliphatic amino acids. While Valine is slightly more bulky than Alanine due to its branched side chain, this substitution is LESS likely to disrupt the alpha-helix significantly compared to introducing proline or charged residues. The change in steric hindrance is not drastic enough to destabilize the helix substantially. Many students might pick this because they recognize that valine is bulkier, but they underestimate the impact of proline or charged residues on secondary structure.''}','{''Lysine and Arginine are both positively charged, basic amino acids. While their side chains differ in structure (lysine has an alkyl chain with an amine, arginine has a guanidinium group), they share similar properties in terms of charge and polarity. This substitution is LESS likely to disrupt the alpha-helix because the overall electrostatic environment is maintained. Students often think of charge as universally disruptive, but maintaining charge type is less destabilizing than changing the charge or introducing proline. This is a distractor.''}','{''Proline is a unique amino acid because its side chain cyclizes and bonds to the nitrogen atom of the amino group, creating a rigid ring structure. This rigidity restricts the conformational flexibility of the peptide backbone and disrupts the regular hydrogen bonding pattern required for alpha-helix formation. Glycine, on the other hand, is very flexible due to its small side chain (just a hydrogen atom) and is often found in turns and loops. Substituting Glycine with Proline introduces significant steric hindrance and disrupts the helix. This is the MOST disruptive substitution among the choices. Many students might overlook the impact of proline on secondary structure, particularly its effect on the alpha-helix. The unique cyclic structure of proline is the key.''}','{"Serine and Threonine are both polar, uncharged amino acids containing hydroxyl (-OH) groups. They are similar in size and polarity. This substitution is LESS likely to significantly disrupt the alpha-helix structure, as the hydrogen bonding potential is largely maintained. The slightly larger methyl group in threonine compared to serine might cause a minor steric effect, but it is not as disruptive as proline. Students might get confused and think Threonine''s slightly bulkier side chain causes disruption, but the effect is minimal compared to the effect of Proline"}',3,2,'A researcher is studying a protein involved in muscle contraction. They discover that a mutation causes a single amino acid substitution within a region of the protein known to be an alpha-helix. Which of the following amino acid substitutions is MOST likely to disrupt the alpha-helical structure?');
INSERT INTO Users_question VALUES(9,'{''1.  AA* significantly improves protein folding at low concentrations (10 µM) compared to the control (0 µM).''}','{''2.  AA* has no effect on protein folding, as the percentage of correctly folded proteins remains relatively constant across all concentrations.''}','{''3.  AA* likely inhibits protein folding in a concentration-dependent manner.''}','{''4.  The optimal concentration of AA* for protein folding is 20 µM, as it has the lowest standard deviation.''}','{"Incorrect. While the percentage of correctly folded proteins is slightly lower at 10 µM AA* compared to 0 µM, the standard deviations overlap significantly (3.2 vs 3.0). This means the difference observed could easily be due to random chance and isn''t statistically significant. A common pitfall is to interpret small numerical differences as meaningful without considering the variability within the data (as indicated by the standard deviation). One would need to perform a statistical test (like a t-test) to determine if the difference is actually significant. Without that, you can''t definitively say there''s a real improvement."}','{''Incorrect. A clear trend of decreasing correctly folded proteins is visible as the AA* concentration increases.  The percentage drops from 85% at 0 µM to 65% at 40 µM. Even though the standard deviations are present, the overall trend demonstrates an effect. While the change between adjacent concentrations might not always be significant on its own, the cumulative effect suggests a real impact. The pitfall here is focusing too much on the standard deviations of individual points and missing the overall trend in the data. Visualizing the data as a graph could help avoid this error.''}','{''Correct. The data clearly shows a decreasing trend in the percentage of correctly folded proteins as the concentration of AA* increases. This suggests that AA* interferes with the protein folding process, and this interference becomes more pronounced at higher concentrations. The trend is consistent despite the standard deviations. A decreasing trend with increasing concentration strongly implies an inhibitory effect that is concentration-dependent. This option is the most justified interpretation of the data provided, as the trend is clear and consistent.''}','{"Incorrect. While 20 µM does have the lowest standard deviation, the percentage of correctly folded proteins at this concentration (78%) is lower than at lower AA* concentrations (0 µM and 10 µM). The goal is typically to maximize the percentage of correctly folded proteins. Choosing a concentration based solely on the lowest standard deviation, while ignoring the actual outcome (percentage folded), is a misinterpretation of the data. Standard deviation reflects precision, but not necessarily accuracy or effectiveness in achieving the desired result. Lower standard deviation means more consistent result, it doesn''t mean best result"}',3,2,replace('A researcher is studying the effects of a novel amino acid analog (AA*) on protein folding. They introduce AA* into a bacterial culture and measure the percentage of correctly folded proteins at different concentrations of AA*. The following data is obtained:\n\n| AA* Concentration (µM) | % Correctly Folded Proteins | Standard Deviation |\n|--------------------------|-----------------------------|----------------------|\n| 0                        | 85                          | 3.2                  |\n| 10                       | 82                          | 3.0                  |\n| 20                       | 78                          | 2.8                  |\n| 30                       | 73                          | 3.5                  |\n| 40                       | 65                          | 3.1                  |\n\nBased on the data, which of the following statements is MOST justified regarding the effect of AA* on protein folding?\n','\n',char(10)));
