        | Vmax (µmol/min) | Km (µM) |\n|-----------------------|-----------------|---------|\n| No Inhibitor          | 100             | 10      |\n| With Inhibitor        | 100             | 20      |\n\nBased on this data, what is the best conclusion about the inhibitor''s effect on the enzyme''s catalytic efficiency?\n','\n',char(10)));
INSERT INTO Users_question VALUES(13,'{''1. A high proportion of proline residues that introduce kinks in the polypeptide chain, disrupting regular secondary structures.''}','{''2. Numerous cysteine residues that form disulfide bonds, cross-linking different parts of the protein and stabilizing its structure.''}','{''3. A large number of amino acids with charged side chains (e.g., glutamate, lysine) that promote electrostatic repulsion and prevent aggregation.''}','{''4. A predominance of small, hydrophobic amino acids (e.g., alanine, valine) that minimize interactions with the surrounding aqueous environment.''}','{"Incorrect. Proline is known to disrupt alpha-helices and beta-sheets due to its rigid cyclic structure and its inability to form hydrogen bonds with the backbone amide hydrogen. If there were a high proportion of proline, the protein would be *less* stable and *more* prone to denaturation, not more resistant. A common pitfall is misremembering proline''s role; it''s a helix breaker, not a stabilizer, so don''t assume rigidity always leads to stability in this context."}','{"Correct. Disulfide bonds, formed between the sulfur atoms of cysteine residues, are covalent bonds that can cross-link different parts of a polypeptide chain or link separate polypeptide chains. These bonds significantly increase the stability of a protein by holding its structure together more tightly, making it more resistant to denaturation. While the question mentions limited tertiary structure, the existence of even a few strategically placed disulfide bridges could dramatically increase stability. Many students might overlook this if they''re overly focused on the lack of tertiary structure, failing to recognize the powerful stabilizing effect of covalent cross-links."}','{''Incorrect. While charged amino acids contribute to protein solubility and can prevent aggregation in an aqueous environment, electrostatic repulsion does not inherently increase the *stability* of the protein structure against denaturation. In fact, excessive charge repulsion could potentially destabilize the folded state if not properly balanced by other stabilizing interactions. The prompt refers to resistance to denaturation, so electrostatic repulsion will do very little. Students selecting this answer might be confusing protein solubility with protein stability; remember that preventing aggregation is different from preventing unfolding.''}','{"Incorrect. While hydrophobic interactions are important for protein folding and stability, a predominance of small, hydrophobic amino acids alone wouldn''t necessarily explain the *exceptional* resistance to denaturation described in the question. Hydrophobic interactions contribute to the overall stability, but are relatively weak compared to covalent disulfide bonds. This option may appeal to those who overemphasize the hydrophobic effect, failing to consider the significance of covalent cross-linking in enhancing stability, especially against harsh conditions. The small size of the amino acids also doesn''t inherently explain the resilience as there would be very little stabilizing Van Der Waals forces as a result. Also it fails to explain the alpha helix/beta sheet composition."}',2,2,'A researcher is studying a novel protein and discovers that it is primarily composed of alpha-helices and beta-sheets, with very little tertiary structure. The protein is found to be highly resistant to denaturation by heat or chemical agents. Which of the following amino acid characteristics would MOST likely contribute to this protein''s unusual stability?');
